            Ankri, Husson et al. have now used various genetic techniques and mutant mice to identify a new population of neurons in the nuclei of the cerebellum and to express fluorescent markers into these cells. This approach reveals that the axons of these neurons ‘climb’ from the nuclei to the cortex to form a new circuit called the inhibitory nucleo-cortical ({iNC}) pathway. Moreover, activating the {iNC} axons with light reveals that they selectively target and silence a population of neurons called the Golgi cells, which control the transmission of information in the cerebellar cortex.
            Ankri, Husson et al. go on to show that the Golgi cells silenced by the {iNC} pathway differ from other Golgi cells in a number of ways: in particular, these Golgi cells use a chemical called {GABA} to communicate with neurons. The next challenge is to explore how the {iNC} pathway fine-tunes how sensory inputs are processed in the cerebellum, and to better understand its role in the execution of complex movements, including in people with conditions that affect motor function, such as ataxias.},
